 the psyche. This book considers the variety of responses to warfare and combat in medieval literature, beginning with a consideration of ideal military practice and the reception of Vegetius, contrasted with Christine de Pisan's treatise on warfare. The collection then turns to chronicling war, particularly in France, Germany and Scotland, and also covers the fictions of war, as presented in English Arthurian narratives, Chaucer, Malory, and pastoral poetry. It concludes with an examination of attitudes to women in warfare. Contributors: MARIANNE AILES, CHRISTOPHERALLMAND, GEORGES LE BRUSQUE, HELEN COOPER, HARRY JACKSON, ANDREW LYNCH, SIMON MEECHAM-JONES, CORINNE SAUNDERS, FRANCOISE LE SAUX, THEA SUMMERFIELD, NEIL E. THOMAS, KEVIN S. WHETTER. CORINNE SAUNDERS and NEIL THOMAS are in the department of English Studies, University of Durham; FRANCOISE LE SAUX is in the department of French at the University of Reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aMilitary art and sciencezEuropexHistoryyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aWar in literature. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aMilitary History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aAiles, Marianne J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAiles, Marianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllmand, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrusque, Georges Le, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, W. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLe Saux, Francoise H M, econtribu